Basic Graphics

Topics to be covered in this section

  1. Line chart
  1. Bar chart
  1. Histogram
  1. Box and whisker plot
  1. Combining plots
  1. Scatterplot matrix

R is an open source software designed mainly for data manipulation, powerful statistics and elegant graphics.

In this tutorial, i will show you how to use R for BASIC graphics [low level plotting commands]. The graphics function is mainly integrated in the base package that comes with R when you install it.

I’m giving an advanced tutorial for more sophisticated graphics using ggplot2 package.

Lets start

lets navigate some demo graphics of the base package in R

Lets start

But we need some data to plot

Lets load some data

Most probably, your data is in an excel file. If so, the most easiest way is to transfer your data from the excel to R through clipboard.

To do that

  1. Paste this code in the console of R

data <- read.table(file=“clipboard”,header=TRUE,sep=“\t”)

  1. Open your excel sheet, highlight your data and press ctrl+C “to copy them”
  1. Put your cursor on your code (step 1), press ctrl+enter
  1. Your data should be stored in R
  1. To confirm, in the upper right panel of R studio, press on “Environment”, you should see your data there.

Try it yourself

Now, we will use a built-in data set in R called mtcars, lets recall this dataset

1. Line chart

Lets plot a line chart where x is a scale and y is the value of (what we want to plot)

For example

plot(mtcars$wt)# plot(data name"data",variable name "represent y axis")

In base graphics, any calls for graphics will remove to the earlier one, simply because the default is to show 1 graph in the panel. try calling another graph

plot(mtcars$drat)

BUT, if you want to show more than 1 graph, you need to setup the panel design first

par(mfrow=c(2,2)) # setting panel 2x2 ### par(mfrow=c(1,1))# to return to default setting 1 graph per window

lets try it using wt, drat, qsec, and hp you should get something like this

my graph

Not difficult right?

Ok, lets add some lines and color

plot(mtcars$hp,type="o",col="red")

In R there is always a wide functionality even in this base function. to know more about any function in details , just type ? before the function name

Try this ? plot

On the latest code typr =“o” means over plot “lines over point”, try exchange it to s, h, or others.

“p” for points, “l” for lines, “b” for both, “c” for the lines part alone of “b”, “o” for both ‘overplotted’, “h” for ‘histogram’ like (or ‘high-density’) vertical lines, “s” for stair steps, “S” for other steps, see ‘Details’ below, “n” for no plotting.

OK clear your plot by pressing on the eraser button (or type “dev.off()”) in the console.

In most cases, we would like to compare several variables

Lets call line graph for the wt

plot(mtcars$wt,type="o", col="blue")

Then ill ask R to overlay the drat data on the existing graph

lines(mtcars$drat,type=“o”,pch=22, col=“red”) # ill change its color to red and points to square

my graph
my graph

Lets add a title for this silly graph

title(main=“my first silly graph!”, col.main=“black”, font.main=4)

my graph

You can change the axis range by calling “ylim=c(0,12)) for y axis and xlim=c(0,50)) for x axis”

plot(mtcars$wt,type="o", col="blue",ylim=c(0,12))

You can always change the x or y axis title

plot(mtcars$wt,type="o", col="blue",xlab="x axis",ylab="y axis")

To add a legend

plot(mtcars$wt,type="o", col="blue",xlab="x axis",ylab="y axis")

Add the legend

legend(1, 5, c(“weight”), col=c(“blue”), cex=0.8, pch=21, lty=1)

cex: for legend box pch: dot shape lty: line shape

Try playing with these parameters

my graph

Lets draw a histogram for y axis

hist(CO2$uptake) # y axis is alway frequency

When drawing a histogram , u need to think about the number of bins to show your data.

Lets compare same graphs with different bins

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
hist(CO2$uptake)
hist(CO2$uptake,breaks=3,col="red")
hist(CO2$uptake,breaks=5,col="blue")
hist(CO2$uptake,breaks=7,col="gold")

You should get this graph

my graph

R chooses how to bin your data for you by default using an algorithm, but if you want coarser or finer groups, you need to define it manually as earlier.

Some tweaks

hist(CO2$uptake, freq=TRUE, xlab="CO data",ylab="uptake frequency", main="CO2 dataset data", col="lightgreen", breaks=9, xlim=c(0,50),pch=16,cex=1.5,cex.lab=1.5,font=2)

Often, we are more interested in density than frequency, since frequency is relative to your sample size. Instead of counting the number of data points per bin, R can give the probability densities using the freq=FALSE option:

The density is calculated as follows: counts/(n*diff(breaks)

Just set frequency=FALSE

hist(CO2$uptake, freq=FALSE, xlab="CO data",ylab="uptake frequency", main="CO2 dataset data", col="lightgreen", breaks=9, xlim=c(0,50),pch=16,cex=1.5,cex.lab=1.5,font=2)

Lets overlay it with distribution curve

curve(dnorm(x, mean=mean(CO2$ uptake), sd=sd(CO2$ uptake)), add=TRUE, col=“darkblue”, lwd=2)

my graph

We can plot the log scale also

plot(CO2$uptake, log="xy", pch=25, col="blue",main="Log-normal distribution",xlab="Value", ylab="Frequency")

4. Box and whisker plot

Box plot is more representative than bar plot in several way

Lets see, Lets use “barplot” dataset that we used earlier

boxplot(for_barplot,col="lightgreen",main="my box plot",xlab="Individuals", ylab="age")

Lets boxplot the mtcars data

boxplot(mtcars,col="lightgreen",main="my box plot",xlab="Individuals", ylab="age")

To understand boxplot, lets discuss this figure

my graph

From this plot you can understand,the differences in medians, interquartile range (fences), and outliers if there is. R calculate this automatically and draw it.

The box plot uses the median and the lower and upper quartiles (defined as the 25th and 75th percentiles). If the lower quartile is Q1 and the upper quartile is Q3, then the difference (Q3 - Q1) is called the interquartile range or IQ.

5. Combining graphics (Moderate tip)

plot(mtcars$drat,mtcars$wt,pch=20,cex=2,col="red") # note that shape 20 is used for filling color but not 21

Adding boxplot to scatter plot

Basically i will set a graph size, define where i would like to put my box plot (fixed), then i will ask R to place the box plots in their locations

par(fig=c(0,0.8,0,0.8), new=TRUE)# setting main size of the scatter plot
## Warning in par(fig = c(0, 0.8, 0, 0.8), new = TRUE): calling par(new=TRUE) with
## no plot
plot(mtcars$drat,mtcars$wt,pch=20,cex=2.5,col="red",font.lab=2)# plottting the main graph # font=2 means bold, 3 means italic
par(fig=c(0,0.8,0.55,1), new=TRUE)#setting the location of the first boxplot for mtcars$drat
boxplot(mtcars$drat, horizontal=TRUE, axes=FALSE,col="gold")# drawing the boxplot of mtcars$drat
par(fig=c(0.65,1,0,0.8),new=TRUE)#setting the location of the first boxplot for mtcars$wt
boxplot(mtcars$wt, axes=FALSE,col="gold")# drawing the boxplot ofmtcars$wt

plot(iris)# this will scatter plot each 2 variable

However, the 5th column shows species name. i dont want that column in my plot. Lets remove it

plot(iris[,1:4])# asking R to plot columns from 1:4 only

We can add some lines to make it easy for eyes to recognize the pattern

pairs(iris[,1:4],panel=panel.smooth)
